echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">African traditional religions at thesis level — faith, doctrine, proselytism, apostasy, birth, marriage, death, metempsychosis, and karma for each tradition.</p>';

// ODINALA
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#2d6a1f;">⊕ Ọdinala (Igbo) — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Panentheistic monism with functional polytheism — Chukwu is One; alusi are aspects | <strong>People:</strong> Igbo (~45 million) | <strong>Status:</strong> Living minority practice alongside Christianity</p>';
echo '<p>See the comprehensive treatment in <a href="/subjects/religion/doctrine/">Doctrine, Dogma & Life Cycle</a> and <a href="/subjects/spirituality/african/">African Esoteric Traditions</a>. Key points summarized here for comparative reference.</p>';
echo '<h3>Faith</h3>';
echo '<p>Ọdinala does not require propositional faith. It is transmitted through participation — in the kola ceremony, the masquerade, the New Yam Festival, the ancestral rites, the four-day market week. Belief is embedded in action. The Igbo phrase "ọ dị n\'ọnụ" (it is in the mouth/on the lips) refers to things spoken but not truly internalized — the opposite of genuine religious commitment, which is demonstrated through practice, not declaration.</p>';
echo '<h3>Monotheism vs Polytheism</h3>';
echo '<p>"Chukwu bu otu" — God is one. The many alusi (deities and spirit forces) are not competitors with Chukwu but instruments of Chukwu\'s presence in specific places and situations. The Aro Chukwu oracle\'s very name means "Voice of the Great God" — the oracle was understood as a direct channel to the supreme divine, not to a lesser deity. This is structurally identical to Hindu understanding: the many devas are aspects of Brahman; the many alusi are aspects of Chukwu.</p>';
echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>None. Ọdinala is the tradition of a specific people in a specific land. It cannot be proselytized because it is not a set of doctrines to be adopted but a set of relationships — with specific ancestors, specific alusi, specific land, specific community — that are entered by birth and initiation, not by declaration of belief.</p>';
echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>No formal mechanism. Social consequences of conversion include exclusion from certain family rituals, inability to perform ancestral rites, and community marginalization in traditional settings. Many Igbo practice dual belonging — Christian in public, maintaining ancestral practice at home.</p>';
echo '<h3>Birth</h3>';
echo '<p>Naming ceremony (igu aha) on the fourth day. Chi acknowledged. Twins (ejima) celebrated as blessings. Ọgbanje identification if the family has suffered repeated infant deaths.</p>';
echo '<h3>Marriage</h3>';
echo '<p>Igba nkwu (wine-carrying ceremony) — the bride carries palm wine to her chosen husband publicly. Ime ego (bride price) negotiated between lineages. Ancestral acknowledgment essential — marriage connects two lineages and their ancestral lines across time.</p>';
echo '<h3>Death and Burial</h3>';
echo '<p>Good death (onwu ọma) celebrated with elaborate ikwa ozu (funeral rites). Bad death treated differently. Burial in the compound — keeping the ancestors close. Masquerades appear as ancestral spirits. Second burial (iwa ọkwa) for prominent persons. Ilo uwa (return) — the deceased will eventually return within the family lineage.</p>';
echo '<h3>Metempsychosis — Ilo Uwa</h3>';
echo '<p>Gender-consistent (man returns as man, woman as woman) and lineage-specific (returning within one\'s family). Not experienced as suffering but as family continuity. The ọgbanje is the pathological case — rapid compulsive cycling — treated as a spiritual disorder requiring healing. See the full comparative treatment at <a href="/subjects/religion/metempsychosis/">Metempsychosis & Karma</a>.</p>';

// YORUBA
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#553c9a;">⊕ Yoruba / Ifá — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Panentheistic — Olodumare is supreme; 401 Orishas are divine principles | <strong>People:</strong> Yoruba (~40 million in origin area) | <strong>Diaspora:</strong> Cuba (Santería), Brazil (Candomblé), Haiti (Vodou elements)</p>';
echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Yoruba religious faith is relational and experiential. One does not "believe in" the Orishas as one might believe a historical claim; one enters into relationship with them through initiation, sacrifice, divination, and devotion. The Ori (personal divine head) chosen before birth is the most intimate divine reality — closer to the individual than any external Orisha. "Ori, my Ori, you who accompanied me from heaven, you who will accompany me home." Faith in Ifá is faith in the reliability of the divination system — the confidence that Orunmila\'s voice, transmitted through the Babalawo, accurately reflects divine truth about one\'s situation.</p>';
echo '<h3>Monotheism vs Polytheism</h3>';
echo '<p>Olodumare is the supreme being — unknowable, unapproachable directly, the source of all existence. The 401 Orishas are divine principles through which Olodumare\'s power manifests in specific domains: Shango = divine justice manifested as thunder; Yemoja = divine nurturing manifested as water; Oshun = divine beauty manifested as rivers and sweetness. Theologically, Yoruba religion is monotheistic at the highest level and functionally polytheistic at the devotional level — structurally identical to Hindu treatment of Brahman and the devas.</p>';
echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Iwa pele (Gentle Character)</strong> — the supreme ethical teaching; "Iwa l\'ewa" — character is beauty; good character is the character of the Orishas; no ritual observance compensates for bad character</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ori (Personal Divinity)</strong> — the divine head-spirit chosen before birth; the most important spiritual relationship; "Honor your Ori before any Orisha"</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ayanmo (Destiny)</strong> — the pre-ordained life path; partially fixed, partially navigable through divination and right action</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ase (Divine Power)</strong> — the creative force/energy of the universe; concentrated in specific people, places, and objects; activated through speech, ritual, and right relationship</li>';
echo '</ul>';
echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Yoruba religion has spread globally through the diaspora rather than through missionary activity. In the Americas, enslaved Yoruba people maintained their religion under conditions of extreme suppression — camouflaging Orishas as Catholic saints in Cuba (Santería), Brazil (Candomblé), and Haiti (Vodou). This diaspora transmission was not proselytism but cultural survival. In the contemporary era, Ifá has developed a global following — non-Africans are initiated into Orisha worship in increasing numbers. Wande Abimbola has argued that Ifá is a universal teaching, not an ethnic tradition.</p>';
echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Leaving the Orisha tradition after initiation is spiritually serious — one has made vows to specific Orishas and the consequences of abandonment are understood as real. However, there is no formal punishment mechanism. Christian and Islamic conversion from Yoruba tradition has been extensive and ongoing since the 19th century; many Yoruba practice a form of dual belonging similar to Igbo dual belonging.</p>';
echo '<h3>Birth</h3>';
echo '<p>Ifá divination for the newborn to determine the child\'s Ori and destiny. Naming on the seventh or ninth day (Isomoloruko). Names encode theology and family history. Twin births (Ibeji) are sacred — Ibeji carvings are made and honored; the death of one twin requires specific rituals.</p>';
echo '<h3>Marriage</h3>';
echo '<p>Ifá consultation for compatibility of destinies. Elaborate multi-stage ceremony involving both families. Bride price negotiation. The wedding feast. Orisha invocations for blessing.</p>';
echo '<h3>Death and Burial</h3>';
echo '<p>The body is washed and dressed. Elaborate funeral ceremonies (Eku Iku). Egungun masquerade tradition — ancestors return to counsel the living. A person of good character (iwa pele) joins the honored ancestors (Ara Orun — citizens of heaven). Bad death — by suicide, execution, or other inauspicious means — prevents the deceased from becoming a beneficial ancestor.</p>';
echo '<h3>Metempsychosis — Atunwa</h3>';
echo '<p>Yoruba reincarnation (atunwa — "to return again") is lineage-specific (Babatunde, Yetunde), generally gender-consistent, and understood through the Ori framework. The returning soul brings its Ori-choice from the previous life. See <a href="/subjects/religion/metempsychosis/">Metempsychosis & Karma</a> for full comparative treatment.</p>';

// AKAN
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#744210;">⊕ Akan Religion — Doctrinal Overview</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Monotheistic (Nyame as supreme) with lesser deities | <strong>People:</strong> Akan (Ashanti, Fante — Ghana, Côte d\'Ivoire)</p>';
echo '<h3>Core Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Nyame</strong> — supreme omniscient God; "Onyame" — the one who alone is full/sufficient; creator and sustainer of all</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Asase Ya</strong> — Earth goddess; second in practical importance to Nyame; no farming on Thursdays (her day); oaths sworn on the earth are among the most serious</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Sunsum</strong> — the personal spirit/essence; the seat of personality, character, and spiritual power; can leave the body during sleep (the source of dreams) or illness</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Kra</strong> — the divine soul given directly by Nyame at birth; returns to Nyame at death; the part of the person that is indestructible</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Stools</strong> — sacred wooden stools are the Akan equivalent of thrones and spiritual repositories; the sunsum of ancestors inhabits ancestral stools; the Golden Stool of the Ashanti is the most sacred object in the tradition — it fell from heaven as a sign of Ashanti destiny and is treated as a living sacred being</li>';
echo '</ul>';
echo '<h3>Birth and Death</h3>';
echo '<p><strong>Birth</strong>: a child is considered a stranger from the spirit world for the first seven days; if it survives, it is named on the eighth day (Outdooring); the name reflects the day of the week on which the child was born (Kofi — Friday male; Ama — Saturday female, etc.). <strong>Death</strong>: elaborate funerals; the deceased is laid in state; funeral cloths reflect the person\'s life and clan; coffins carved in the shape of the deceased\'s profession or interest (fisherman in a fish-shaped coffin, pilot in a plane-shaped coffin) are a modern Ghanaian tradition; the deceased\'s soul (kra) returns to Nyame; the sunsum may remain close to family.</p>';
echo '<h3>Reincarnation</h3>';
echo '<p>Akan tradition holds that ancestors can return through the female (mogya — blood) line. This creates a distinctively matrilineal dimension — souls return through their mothers\' lineages. The concept is less elaborated than Igbo or Yoruba atunwa but present in traditional belief.</p>';

// ZULU
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#1a365d;">⊕ Zulu / Nguni Religion — Doctrinal Overview</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Ancestral — Amadlozi (ancestors) are the primary spiritual agents; Unkulunkulu as creator | <strong>People:</strong> Zulu, Xhosa, Swazi, Ndebele (South Africa)</p>';
echo '<h3>Core Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Amadlozi (Ancestors)</strong> — the most important spiritual beings in daily Zulu life; the dead do not depart but remain active in the family\'s affairs; they protect descendants when properly honored; they cause illness and misfortune when neglected or offended; maintaining right relationships with ancestors is the primary religious obligation</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Unkulunkulu</strong> — "the Ancient One" or "the Greatest"; the first being, sometimes described as a creator who emerged from a reed bed and created all life; his role varies by interpretation — some treat him as creator god, others as the first ancestor</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ubuntu</strong> — "I am because we are"; the foundational Nguni ethical principle; personhood is constituted through relationship with others, not through individual existence; a person who does not maintain community relationships has no personhood in the full sense; Ubuntu is simultaneously a philosophy of ethics, a theory of personhood, and a description of how the divine works through human community</li>';
echo '</ul>';
echo '<h3>The Isangoma (Diviner)</h3>';
echo '<p>The isangoma is called by the ancestors through a specific illness (ukuthwasa — the "coming out" sickness). This illness cannot be treated by conventional medicine — it is the ancestors\' demand that the person accept their call and undergo initiation as a diviner. The isangoma is typically female (though male isangoma exist). After initiation, she can communicate with the ancestors, diagnose spiritual causes of illness, and prescribe remedies. The isangoma is the most important spiritual specialist in Zulu society — more important than the herbalist (inyanga) or the sorcerer (umthakathi).</p>';
echo '<h3>Birth, Marriage, and Death</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Birth</strong>: mother and child are in a state of ritual vulnerability; specific medicines and rituals protect them; the baby\'s name reflects the circumstances of its birth and the family\'s relationship with ancestors</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Marriage</strong>: lobola (cattle payment) is the central marriage institution; cattle are not a "bride price" but a symbol of covenant between families; the exchange establishes the husband\'s lineage\'s claim over the children of the marriage and the wife\'s new spiritual affiliation; a woman who has not been properly "lobolaed" is not fully married in the traditional sense</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Death</strong>: elaborate mourning customs; the deceased is told they are dying and encouraged to accept their transition; the body is buried facing east (toward the rising sun); cattle may be slaughtered at the funeral to accompany the deceased; the mourning period (ukuzila) lasts several months; after its conclusion, specific rituals bring the deceased into the family\'s ancestral company (ukubuyisa — "bringing home")</li>';
echo '</ul>';

